5/30/14<br>
<a name="troll-or-idiot"><b>Troll or idiot?</b></a>
<p>
<center><a href="http://wattsupwiththat.com/2014/05/30/friday-funny-new-drought-trigger-postulated-for-csiro-to-study/"><img src="drought_trigger.jpg"><br>
Via Watts Up With That</a></center><p>
<p>
I'd like to think that someone successfully trolled the paper, but the sad fact is that I've personally met people (including at least one alleged college graduate) who professed to believe that DST <i>does</i> increase the length of the day.*
<p>
(As it happpens,  this is a <a href="http://www.performancecontroller.com/2012/05/the-daylight-saving-theory-on-the-cause-of-the-10-year-droughts-in-australia/">fairly old story</a> from October 2008. But still funny.)
<p>
<hr width=20 align=left>
* <font size=2>The belief generally seems to be based on observations that DST starts in in the spring, and that's when days get longer, therefore... <i>correlation <b>does</b> equal causation abracadabra presto  TA DA!</i> Noting that, post summer solstice, days get <i>shorter</i> with DST still in effect results in a dismissive,"You just don't understand," or blank looks reminescent of deer in the headlights.</font>
